I can actually asking this:

```
std::string certURL =
            "/redfish/v1/AccountService/LDAP/Certificates/" + id;
sdbusplus::message::object_path path(certs::ldapObjectPath);
path /= id;
```

There are two styles of contacting paths ("${a}/" + b, vs using sdbusplus) in the same code. Should we use the same way? 

Why is it related to constexpr constructor of object_path?

> constexpr sdbusplus::message::object_path ldapObjectPath = "...";

Currently object_path is a wrapper of std::string, which cannot be constexpr. (I know C++20 supports constexpr std::string, but it requires the allocation being cleaned up in constexpr evaluation time, which is not our case)

Or something like `static const sdbusplus::message::object_path ldapObjPath("...");` can be used, but it is not as clean as we want I think.
